Therefore, the area inside circle $\mathcal{C}$ but outside the six smaller circles is equal to the area of circle $\mathcal{C}$ minus the area of the six smaller circles, plus the area of sector $AOB.$  Thus,
\[K = \pi \cdot 30^2 - 6 \pi r^2 + \frac{1}{3} \cdot \pi (2r)^2.\]Substituting $r = 30 - 2\sqrt{3},$ we get
\[K = \pi \cdot 30^2 - 6 \pi (30 - 2\sqrt{3})^2 + \frac{1}{3} \cdot \pi (4(30 - 2\sqrt{3}))^2.\]Then
\begin{align*}
K &= 900 \pi - 6 \pi (270 - 120\sqrt{3} + 12) + \frac{16}{3} \pi (870 - 120\sqrt{3}) \\
&= 900 \pi - 6 \pi (282 - 120\sqrt{3}) + \frac{16}{3} \pi (870 - 120\sqrt{3}) \\
&= 900 \pi + 16 \pi (870 - 120\sqrt{3}) - 6 \pi (282 - 120\sqrt{3}) \\
&= 900 \pi + 16 \pi \cdot 870 - 6 \pi \cdot 282 \\
&\quad - 16 \pi \cdot 120\sqrt{3} + 6 \pi \cdot 120\sqrt{3} \\
&= 900 \pi + 16 \pi \cdot 870 - 6 \pi \cdot 282 - 10 \pi \cdot 120\sqrt{3}.
\end{align*}Since $\pi < 3.15,$
\[900 \pi + 16 \pi \cdot 870 - 6 \pi \cdot 282 - 10 \pi \cdot 120\sqrt{3} < 900 \cdot 3.15 + 16 \cdot 870 \cdot 3.15 - 6 \cdot 3.15 \cdot 282 - 10 \cdot 3.15 \cdot 120 \cdot 1.8,\]which simplifies to $2689.2.$  Therefore, $\lfloor K \rfloor = \boxed{2689}.$

Solution:
Let $r$ be the radius of each of the six congruent circles.  Then the radius of the circle that passes through the points of tangency of the six circles is $r\sqrt{3},$ and the radius of the circle that passes through their centers is $2r.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

path outer = Circle((0,0),30);
pair[] O;
