Then $r + r\sqrt{3} + 2r = 30,$ so $r = 30/(2 + \sqrt{3}).$

The area of the region inside $\cal C$ and outside all of the six circles in the ring is equal to the area of $\cal C$ minus the sum of the areas of the six congruent circles.  Thus, we get
\begin{align*}
K &= \pi \cdot 30^2 - 6 \cdot \pi r^2 \\
&= 900 \pi - 6 \cdot \pi \cdot \frac{30^2}{(2 + \sqrt{3})^2} \\
&= 900 \pi - 6 \cdot \pi \cdot \frac{900}{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= 900 \pi - \frac{5400 \pi}{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= 900 \pi \cdot \frac{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}}{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}} - \frac{5400 \pi}{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= 6300 \pi + 2160 \pi \sqrt{3} - \frac{5400 \pi}{7 + 4 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= 6300 \pi + 2160 \pi \sqrt{3} - \frac{5400 \pi (7 - 4 \sqrt{3})}{49 - 48} \\
&= 6300 \pi + 2160 \pi \sqrt{3} - 300 \pi (7 - 4 \sqrt{3}) \\
&= 6300 \pi + 2160 \pi \sqrt{3} - 2100 \pi + 1200 \pi \sqrt{3} \\
&= 4200 \pi + 3360 \pi \sqrt{3}.
\end{align*}Thus, $\lfloor K \rfloor = \boxed{11949}.$

Solution:
Let the radius of each of the small circles be $r$, and let $O$ be the center of $\mathcal{C}$.  Let $A$ and $B$ be adjacent centers of the small circles.  Then $\angle AOB = 60^\circ$, so $\triangle AOB$ is equilateral.  Let $M$ be the midpoint of $\overline{AB}$, and let $N$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $O$ to $\overline{AB}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

